    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-19T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-19T07:00:00-05:00" n="158"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d158">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/9815</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-19T13:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 19, 1918, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 2.45 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1178. War Trade Board [from <persName>Frothingham</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 1259. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_FPj1">Fuller</persName>. Your
                    754, July 2, and despatch July 1.<note n="1" xml:id="d158fn1">Despatch not
                        printed.</note> Our 1182, August 8. The French member of conference now
                    proposes, on the basis of a communication from his Government, to include in
                    classes of exceptional cases which are not to be referred to conference, all
                    trading-with-the-enemy transactions to which an Allied or neutral government is
                    a party. British and United States representatives are of opinion that this
                    classification will include many cases which it is desirable should be subject
                    to reference. In view of this disagreement, conference considers it is desirable
                    that question should be discussed in Washington by Allied representatives <pb
                        facs="0203" n="1037" xml:id="pg_1037"/> where plan originated. Italian
                    representative on inter-Allied committee for correlation of published black
                    lists, which has been designated as the conference to consider these
                    applications, states that his Government is still unwilling to accept the plan.
                    The principle the conference assumes that until question of exceptional cases is
                    settled, no more specific applications will be submitted. We understand the
                    British have telegraphed their Embassy in Washington to the same effect.
                        <persName>Frothingham</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
